  <fragment slot="intro">
    Leaking faucets, running toilets, clogged drains, broken shower heads. We repair and install bathroom fixtures. Quick fixes and full fixture upgrades.
  </fragment>

  ## Common Bathroom Problems

  **Leaking faucets** — A dripping tap wastes 3,000 gallons per year and runs up your water bill. Usually the fix is a washer or cartridge replacement, which takes 20 minutes.

  **Running toilets** — The flapper or fill valve wears out. Water runs from the tank into the bowl constantly. Another 200+ gallons per day down the drain.

  **Clogged drains** — Hair, soap, and debris build up. Water drains slowly or not at all. Often cleared with a plunger or drain snake; sometimes needs P-trap removal and cleaning.

  **Low water pressure** — Corroded aerators, mineral buildup, or supply line issues. A simple aerator cleaning often fixes it.

  **Broken fixtures** — Shower heads, handles, towel racks, medicine cabinets. These get bumped, age, and fail.

  ## What We Fix

  **Faucet repair and replacement** — Leaking faucets get rebuilt (new washers, cartridges, or valve seats) or replaced entirely. We install single-handle and dual-handle faucets, wall-mounted, and vessel sink models.

  **Toilet repair and replacement** — Running toilets get a new flapper or fill valve (cheap fix). Cracked bowls or tanks get replaced. We remove the old toilet, install a new one, and ensure proper seal and caulking.

  **Drain cleaning** — We use a plunger, drain snake, or wet vacuum to clear clogs. If the P-trap is clogged, we remove it, clean it, and reinstall. For tougher blockages, we may recommend a plumber with a drain camera and power auger.

  **Shower and tub repair** — Leaking or corroded shower heads get replaced. Diverters (the valve that switches between tub and shower) get rebuilt or replaced. We also handle caulk removal and resealing.

  **Fixture installation** — New vanities, towel racks, shelving, mirrors, and lighting. We rough-in supply and drain lines if needed, or tie into existing lines.

  **Ventilation fans** — Bathroom exhaust fans prevent mold and humidity damage. We install, repair, and connect to proper ducting that vents outside (not into the attic).

  ## When to Call a Plumber vs. a Handyman

  Most fixture repair and replacement is handyman work. However, if the job requires:
  - New rough-in plumbing (extending supply or drain lines into walls)
  - Tie-in to the main water line or septic system
  - Gas line work (tankless water heaters)
  - Significant wall opening or framing

  ...then a licensed plumber is required. We can help with fixture installation if the rough-in already exists.

  ## Cost & Timeline

  - Faucet repair: $150–$300
  - Faucet replacement: $300–$700
  - Toilet repair: $100–$250
  - Toilet replacement: $400–$1,000
  - Drain cleaning: $150–$400
  - Shower head or tile caulk: $100–$300
  - Exhaust fan installation: $300–$600

  Most jobs take 2–4 hours.

  ## Prevention

  - Clean aerators and shower heads annually (soak in vinegar to dissolve mineral deposits).
  - Don't pour grease down drains—use a drain strainer.
  - Ventilate the bathroom after showers (run the exhaust fan for 20 minutes).
  - Caulk and seal around tubs and showers annually.

